<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-finiteness" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Finiteness
  </title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Before we brave the unintuitive mess which is the realm of infinite sets, we will rigorously develop a notion of size for sets which contain only finitely many elements. Like in the infinite case, these finite cardinalities will be based on bijections.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <proposition xml:id="proposition-injections-of-finite-sets">
    <title>
      Injections of finite sets
    </title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any natural numbers <m> m , n \in \N </m>, there exists an injective map <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m> if and only if <m> m \leq n </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m> m \leq n </m>, then <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \subseteq \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m>, and so the inclusion map <m> \iota_{ \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } }^{ \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } } \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m> is an injective map from <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } </m> to <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m>. So it suffices to show the reverse implication.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        To that end, consider the subset
        
        <md>
          S = \setmid{ m \in \N }{ \textrm{There are } n \in \N \textrm{ and } f \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } \textrm{ so that } m \not \leq n \textrm{ and } f \textrm{ is injective} }
        </md>
        
        of the natural numbers <m> \N </m>. If suffices to show that <m> S = \emptyset </m>. To that end, we first note that <m> 0 \leq n </m> for all natural numbers <m> n \in \N </m>, so that <m> 0 \notin S </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Now let <m> m \in \N </m> be a natural number, and suppose that <m> m + 1 \in S </m>. Then there is a natural number <m> n \in \N </m> so that <m> m + 1 \not \leq n </m> and an injective function <m> f \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m + 1 } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m>. We note that <m> n \neq 0 </m>, since there are no functions from a non-empty set <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m + 1 } </m> to the empty set <m> \emptyset </m>. Thus <m> n = p + 1 </m> for some natural number <m> p \in \N </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        If <m> m \leq p </m>, then <m> m + 1 \leq p + 1 = n </m>, and so <m> m \not \leq p </m>. It therefore suffices to construct an injective function <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , p } </m>. To that end, fix a bijection <m> g \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , p + 1 } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , p + 1 } </m> so that <m> g \of{ f \of{ m + 1 } } = p + 1 </m>, and let <m> h \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , p } </m> be the function defined by the formula
        
        <md>
          h \of{ j } = g \of{ f \of{ j } }
        </md>.
        
        Since <m> g </m> and <m> f </m> are injective, <m> h </m> is injective by (a) of <xref provisional="problem-compositions-of-injections-surjections-and-bijections"/>. We conclude that <m> n \in S </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        In summary, we have shown that <m> 0 \notin S </m> and for all natural numbers <m> n \in \N </m>, if <m> n + 1 \in S </m>, then <m> n \in S </m>. These conclusions are equivalent to <m> 0 \in \N \setminus S </m> and for all natural numbers <m> n \in \N </m>, if <m> n \in \N \setminus S </m>, then <m> n + 1 \in \N \setminus S </m>. We conclude that <m> \N \setminus S = \N </m> by the axiom of induction, and so <m> S = \emptyset </m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <corollary xml:id="corollary-finite-cardinality-is-well-defined">
    <title>
      Finite cardinality is well-defined
    </title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any set <m> X </m>, if there are natural numbers <m> m , n \in \N </m> and bijections <m> f \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to X </m> and <m> g \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } \to X </m>, then <m> m = n </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        Under the given assumptions, <m> g^{ -1 } \circ f \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } </m> and <m> f^{ -1 } \circ g \colon \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } \to \set{ 1 , \dotsc , m } </m> are injective functions by (a) of <xref provisional="problem-compositions-of-injections-surjections-and-bijections"/>. <xref ref="proposition-injections-of-finite-sets"/> now implies that <m> m \leq n </m> and <m> n \leq m </m>, and so <m> m = n </m> by (2) of <xref ref="proposition-comparison-is-a-total-order"/>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </corollary>

  <definition xml:id="definition-finiteness-cardinality">
    <title>
      Finiteness; cardinality
    </title>
    
    <idx>
      finite
    </idx>
    
    <idx>
      cardinality
    </idx>
    
    <idx>
      infinite
    </idx>
    
    <notation>
      <usage>
        <m> \card{ X } </m>
      </usage>
      
      <description>
        <p>
          the cardinality of <m> X </m>
        </p>
      </description>
    </notation>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        A set <m> X </m> is called <term> finite </term> if there is a natural number <m> n \in \N </m> and a bijection <m> \set{ 1 , \dotsc , n } \to X </m>, in which case <m> n </m> is uniquely defined by this property and is called the <term> cardinality </term> of <m> X </m> and denoted <m> \card{ X } = n </m>. A set <m> X </m> is called <term> infinite </term> if no such number and bijection exist.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <proposition xml:id="proposition-maps-and-cardinality">
    <title>
      Maps and cardinality
    </title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m> f \colon X \to Y </m> be a map from a set <m> X </m> to a set <m> Y </m>.
        
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m> f </m> is injective and <m> Y </m> is finite, then <m> X </m> is finite and <m> \card{ X } \leq \card{ Y } </m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m> f </m> is surjective and <m> X </m> is finite, then <m> Y </m> is finite and <m> \card{ Y } \leq \card{ X } </m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m> f </m> is bijective and either <m> X </m> or <m> Y </m> is finite, then both <m> X </m> and <m> Y </m> are finite and <m> \card{ X } = \card{ Y } </m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Text after the last subdivision.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</subsection>

